bio:
About

We are Swindon Makerspace. We like to break and make things. Many different things – robots, aircraft, computers, electronics – anything goes.

How we Began

Originally formed as the Swindon Hackspace in June 2012, as a weekly meeting for those interested in making, breaking, and fixing things. Up until March 2016, we were hosted by the Museum of Computing, and had free use of the basement space. However, our expansion was held back by the limited space available and no 24×7 access.

After nearly 4 years, we took the plunge and signed a lease on a dedicated industrial unit to allow our membership and tool base to grow. We’re now working hard to make that space as functional and well featured as possible, whilst drawing in new members to make sure we’re sustainable.

What our Members Get Up To

Members work on a range of projects that usually involve electronic hardware, software programming, and mechanical assembly.

We encourage each other to run informal workshops on topics such as Solar Power, Laser Cutting, OpenSCAD, and 3D Printing. We also run workshops for the public several times a year – check our Events calendar for details.

Weekly Open Night

We meet regularly on Wednesday evenings from around 6:30pm for our open and social evening – anyone that’s interested in visiting the space is welcome to pop in for a tour/chat and see what’s going on.

If you’re not quite ready for a full membership, you’re also welcome to pay on the door to use the space – it’s £5 for the evening, or for an entire day if escorted by another member (i.e. if you’re friends with an existing member).

You’re strongly encouraged to bring along works in progress, new and interesting hardware, or any other projects or shiny gadgets. We love to help with other peoples projects (much easier than working on your own) and are more than happy to introduce you to the various tools.

The site has free parking, and we have free WiFi and tea/coffee facilities in the space.

I was born a poor white boy on a cold spring night in a small town in Michigan... wait that is going to far back in my story...

I first learned about 3D printing in college around 2006, I built a Prusa Mendel back in September 2012 as my first printer. Then I backed the Robo3D on kickstarter, then I was the caretaker of a Makergear M2 for a FIRST Robotics team, then in 2017 I bought a Monoprice Delta Mini for a good deal,and in 2019 I bought a Ender 3.

Physics student at Leeds University. I built a Rapman that lives in the QIX department, which we want to use to print mounts for optics equipment, (these consist mainly of flat shaped blocks, i.e. with z axis is the critical dimension).
And working with polymer physicists to test some material properties of FFM/FDM'ed material, with the aim of creating build rules. So that for example the type of infill would be changed depending on whether the part was under compression, torque, tension etc.
These could then be automated within skeinforge.

bio:
I went to school as a mechanical engineer, and got interested in 3D modeling, specifically the SDRC I-DEAS CAD/CAM software system. This interest got me my first job working for a CAD/CAM reseller doing pre and post-sales support. I was lucky to be involved in 3D printing in the early 90s - for a demo of rapid prototyping, I modeled the mouse from my HP-UX CAD workstation and it was rendered via stereolithography. I still have that model, but across the years I stopped using CAD and moved to systems administration. Now that 3D printing is affordable and mostly reliable, I've gotten into it and am having a blast. I printed all the usual cute little trinkets and tchotchkes, but quickly got bored of that. What I find most interesting is needing something, then spending a little bit of time in a CAD program and soon after that having a real, functional version of the part in my hand.

I'm a cyclist and bike mechanic as a hobby and a side job, and have found endless applications of 3D printing to both bikes and bike maintenance. Coworkers have also come to me with many varied requests, each of which has been an interesting challenge and an opportunity to learn.

I am constantly learning, constantly trying to challenge myself to learn new things and technologies, so hopefully as I progress my designs will continue to improve.

Brandyn Metzko is a composer, conductor, performer and music teacher. Brandyn Metzko earned his Bachelor of Arts Degree in MusicSumma Cum Laude from Cleveland State University in 2006, where he studied flute with Sean Gabriel, voice with William Dempsey, and conducting with Dr. Betsy Burleigh. In 2015 Brandyn was awarded the Master’s of Science Degree in Entertainment Business from top-ranked Full Sail University in Orlando, Florida.
Brandyn has had thriving private teaching studios in Central Florida, New York City, San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Cleveland preparing students for milestones ranging from orchestra, conservatory and opera auditions to American Idol performances. Brandyn teaches voice, flute, clarinet, saxophone, recorder, trumpet, French horn, trombone, tuba, violin, viola, cello, percussion, jazz improvisation, ensemble conducting, music theory, music history and composition.
Brandyn helped to found the Blazing River Freedom Band in Cleveland in 2003, the Bay Area Rainbow Symphony in San Francisco in 2007, and the Queer Urban Orchestra in New York City in 2009. He has served on the national board of the Lesbian/Gay Band Association as Membership Services Chair. Brandyn served as Artistic Director of the Blazing River Freedom Band from 2003 until 2007 and again from 2011 until 2014. He was co-artistic director of the Queer Urban Orchestra in 2009-2010, and was the assistant music director if the Central Florida Sounds of Freedom Band in 2012.
Brandyn’s performance credits include solo and chamber works; studio recording; sacred, operatic, Broadway and popular vocal music; performance in chamber ensembles, flute choir, wind band, orchestra, jazz ensemble, chorale, and pop/rock band. He was an active performing member of the Space Coast Flute Orchestra and the Indialantic Chamber Singers in Central Florida during 2012. He has performed with the Cuyahoga Community College West Campus’ Wind Ensemble as principal flute and piccolo since 2013.
Brandyn performs throughout the Midwest on flute, clarinet, saxophone and voice in a variety of professional venues. He is also one of the section leaders at Queen Mary of Peace church in Brooklyn, Ohio and sings with the church’s paid professional Schola chamber chorale.
Brandyn’s work as a composer is quite diverse. While the catalog of his published work heavily features chamber and wind band arrangements, he has also written several original pieces. Never content to stick with the tried and true, during recent years Brandyn has expanded his writing to include jazz, rock, pop, dance, house and electronica.

bio: I teach a course called Modular Technology to 8th grade students. It is an essentially a Makers Space that I have been running for more than 20 years now. I have more than 30 modular areas that students can pick from. I have used grants to land 5 3D printers, A replicator 2x, 2 and my new baby is a printrbot simple. I am not a master of any software, but have always been able to pick tools up and put them to use. I love experimenting and lean towards free tools so that my students can afford them at home as well.

I am an architectural draftsman, tabletop gamer, and supporter of information freedom. Most of my designs here are intended for tabletop games like Dungeons & Dragons, Warhammer 40K, Savage Worlds, Malifaux, and the like.

We are a company based in Turin, Italy, and our aim is to make 3D printing cheaper and more ecological!

Our main project, Felfil Evo, is an easy to use filament extruder that allow anyone to produce, by their own, the filament needed for their 3D printer, starting from industrial plastic, wastes or wrong 3D-printed models.

Our projects are proudly open source, so if you cannot afford them, why not to try to build them by your own?
